com.seagullsw.appinterface.client.java

Class AppInterfaceCommand

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.seagullsw.appinterface.client.java.AppInterfaceCommand

  • public abstract class AppInterfaceCommand
extends java.lang.Object

    The abstract class AppInterfaceCommand is the system-supplied base "application command bean" (or "host function access bean") class. Being abstract, the class cannot be instantiated. Rather, all concrete command bean classes extend AppInterfaceCommand and inherit its public API, elaborated below.

    A command bean is a Java class that enables a Java client program to invoke a particular application interface function. Command beans are generated by the Interface Definition Tool as an option for the publication of interface functions. As command beans, together with some runtime classes (e.g. the interface AppInterfaceConnection), take care of all XML data encoding/decoding and all details of the (several flavors of) communications protocol with the AIS, they provide an easy way to access defined host applications via Java.

    In addition to the protocol inherited from their superclass, generated command beans provide methods for setting the input argument values --- setArg_xxx() --- and retrieving the output result values --- getResult_xxx(). These methods cannot be part of the generic AppInterfaceCommand API because they are specific to a particular command bean's interface function and hence different for each command bean class. On the other hand, for example, the AppInterfaceCommand execute() method can be invoked on an arbitrary command bean in order to execute the bean's interface function.

    See Also:
    AppInterfaceConnection, AppInterfaceConnectionFactory, AppInterfaceCommandInvocationException, AppInterfaceCommandFailureResponseException, AppInterfaceCommandIllegalStateException, AppInterfaceCommandUnknownDataElementException

    • Constructor Detail

      • AppInterfaceCommand

        public AppInterfaceCommand()

        This constructor configures the new command bean to communicate with an AIS via a default AppInterfaceConnection instantiated automatically by the static factory method:
        AppInterfaceConnectionFactory.createDefaultConnection().

        The default connection is the client of a socket at IP address "localhost" and port defined by the int constant com.seagullsw.appinterface.comm.AppInterfaceCommunicationConstants.DEFAULT_SOCKET_PORT (e.g. 1208).

        Alternatively, the command bean can be configured with a different connection, for remote AIS communication via a desired socket (at a specified IP address and port number) or using HTTP, by passing that connection to the one-argument command bean constructor:
        AppInterfaceCommand(AppInterfaceConnection).

        Every generated command bean subclass of AppInterfaceCommand is endowed with an analogous constructor, which simply calls super(), i.e. this constructor.

        See Also:
        AppInterfaceConnectionFactory

      • AppInterfaceCommand

        public AppInterfaceCommand(AppInterfaceConnection connection)

        Configures a new command bean to communicate with an AIS with the given AppInterfaceConnection. A socket, HTTP, or other connection can be provided.

        For example: 

         AppInterfaceConnectionFactory.createSocketConnection(String ipAddress, int portNumber)
        or 
         AppInterfaceConnectionFactory.createHTTPConnection(String ipAddress)

        Every generated command bean subclass of AppInterfaceCommand is endowed with an analogous constructor, which simply calls super(connection), i.e. this constructor.

        See Also:
        AppInterfaceConnectionFactory

      • execute

        public void execute()
             throws AppInterfaceCommandInvocationException,
                    AppInterfaceCommandFailureResponseException

        Executes the command bean's application interface function, after arguments have been set in the request, and stores the response for subsequent retrieval of results.

        Note that, while the request is automatically instantiated and initialized with the function name by the command bean's init()method, prior to invoking execute() a client of the command bean is responsible for setting all required input argument values in the request by issuing calls to bean-specific setArg_xxx() methods.

        If the bean's AppInterfaceConnectionobject has not explicitly been opened with AppInterfaceConnection.open(), then the connection will automatically be opened, the request executed in a separate session, and finally the connection closed. Alternatively, the bean's connection may first be opened explicitly, after which all subsequent invocations of execute() will be processed in the same session until the connection is explicitly closed with AppInterfaceConnection.close().

        Throws:
        AppInterfaceCommandInvocationException - if execution was unable to complete
        AppInterfaceCommandFailureResponseException - if execution completed, but with a failure code in the response
        AppInterfaceCommandIllegalStateException - if the command bean is not in the "initialized" state

        See Also:
        setExecute(boolean)

      • getRequest

        public com.seagullsw.appinterface.model.data.Request getRequest()

        Returns the Request object that serves to encapsulate the input arguments for the command bean's application interface function invocation. This request is initialized automatically with the function name at bean initialization time -- see the init()method.

        The argument data values can conveniently be set by client calls to the bean-specific setArg_xxx() methods (invoked on the command bean itself). Moreover, after having been set, these values may be retrieved by calls to the bean's corresponding getArg_xxx() methods.

      • init

        public void init()

        Initializes the application command bean.

        In particular, asks the command bean's AppInterfaceConnectionto create a Request object, initialized with the interface function name, which will be used by the command bean to process interface function invocation requests, that is, calls to the execute()method.

        This method is overridden by every concrete command bean subclass, as follows: set the bean's application interface function name with (protected) setFunctionName() and then call super.init(), in that precise order.

        After init() is called, the bean will answer true to isNew()and false to isInitialized()if any required input properties need to be set; once all required arguments have been set, it will answer false to isNew()and true to isInitialized().

        An attempt to execute()a bean that is not in the "initialized" state, or else to extract one of its arguments with a call to a generated getArg_xxx() method, will raise an AppInterfaceCommandIllegalStateException.

        This method may be called by clients to restore the bean to its originally constructed state, in particular clearing the function arguments by initializing a new request object for the bean.

      • initRequest

        protected void initRequest()
        Initializes the command bean's Request object, as follows: (1) Ask the connection to create a request object whose "name" attribute is the name of the command bean's application interface function. Setting this function name must the first action of the init() method of any application command bean, that is, concrete AppInterfaceCommand subclass. (2) Caches this request object in the command bean's request field. [IvanF 18-January-2000] Is this really a good idea ???

      • isExecuted

        public boolean isExecuted()

        Returns true if the command bean is in the "executed" state. The three public command bean states are "new", "initialized", and "executed".

        The bean enters the "executed" state when its execute()method has stored a response, even in the event that a response failure code is indicated by execute()throwing an AppInterfaceCommandFailureResponseException.

        An attempt to extract a result from a bean that is not in the "executed" state, with a call to a generated getResult_xxx() method, will raise an AppInterfaceCommandIllegalStateException.

        NOTE: The "initialized" and "executed" states are not mutually exclusive. Once the bean is "executed", it remains "initialized" so long as its required input properties (if any) remain set.

      • isInitialized

        public boolean isInitialized()

        Returns true if the command bean is in the "initialized" state. The three public command bean states are "new", "initialized", and "executed".

        The bean moves from the "new" state to the "initialized" state once all its required function invocation arguments (input properties) have been set.

        An attempt to execute()a bean that is not in the "initialized" state, or else to extract one of its arguments with a call to a generated getArg_xxx() method, will raise an AppInterfaceCommandIllegalStateException.

      • isNew

        public boolean isNew()

        Returns true if the command bean is in the "new" state. The three public command bean states are "new", "initialized", and "executed".

        The bean acquires the "new" state upon construction, remaining there until all required function arguments (input properties) have been set.

      • reset

        public void reset()

        Resets the command bean's "executed" state to false and nulls out any previous response. As a consequence, any attempt to query the bean for its result values, as with a call to a generated getResult_xxx() method, will throw an AppInterfaceCommandIllegalStateExceptionuntil the bean is executed again. The argument values remain unaffected, and may be retrieved (if desired) with getArg_xxx() calls, as usual.

        Any (including none) or all of the arguments can be set again with setArg_xxx() calls and then the bean re-executed with a call to execute(). Note, however, that a command bean is not required to be reset prior to being re-executed, since the new response object will simply replace the previous one. So, the primary purpose of reset() is to disable the extraction of result values, making re-execution mandatory.

        NOTE: By contrast, the init()method (overridden by concrete subclasses) may be called by clients to restore the bean to its originally constructed state, in particular clearing the function arguments by initializing a new request object for the bean.

      • setExecute

        public void setExecute(boolean invokeExecute)
                throws AppInterfaceCommandInvocationException,
                       AppInterfaceCommandFailureResponseException

        This method is provided for the benefit for Java Server Pages (JSP) and other JavaBean-oriented application development tools. Some such tools support automatic access of bean properties only, rather than methods.

        In support of this, setExecute() provides a way of setting what may be regarded as an "execute property," purely for the side-effect of invoking the execute()method on the bean. The only legal argument to this method is true, in which case the effect is entirely equivalent to having called the execute()method on the command bean directly. Passing a false argument throws an IllegalArgumentException.

        Throws:
        AppInterfaceCommandInvocationException - if execution was unable to complete
        AppInterfaceCommandFailureResponseException - if execution completed, but with a failure code in the response
        AppInterfaceCommandIllegalStateException - if the command bean is not in the "initialized" state
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if any argument other than true is supplied

        See Also:
        execute()

      • verifyInitialized

        protected void verifyInitialized()
        State "initialized": second of the three command bean states ("new", "initialized", "executed") prescribed by the IBM Command interface. According to that specification, a command bean is in the "new" state upon instantiation and enters the "initialized" state precisely when all its required input properties have been set. Since we don't yet distinguish any such required arguments, currently the only conditions for a command bean to be "initialized" are that (1) its application interface function name be known, and (2) its request object exist. These conditions are always satisfied automatically by command bean instantiation. In the future this behavior can be expanded to check for the presence of required inputs.
